@EndNode
@Node "Filtration" "DzDir.guide/Filtration and Searching"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
You may filter in four main ways:

Files & Directories: This is only valid with Filters, and tells DzDir which, if any, file-
type you wish to apply this Filter to.

Name: just choose a preset name, or put in an AmigaDos style wildcard, eg. 
F#?.info.

Size: You may choose a minimum and maximum size to Filter/search on or an exact 
value, this size is in Bytes.

Date: You may choose a minimum and maximum date to Filter/search on or an exact 
value, This age is in Days relative to today Ie. 1 is yesterday, 6 is today last 
week.

Datatype: You may wish to filter out all files that are not IFF's but they don't have a 
.IFF tail. Just pick IFF and thats all the list will accept. You can of course filter 
on more than one type.

These ways of filtering are logically ANDed together, so you can filter on name a#? 
between 0-10K big, made 3 days ago that is a (JPEG, GIF, IFF or EPS). 
@EndNode
@Node "Registration" "DzDir.guide/Registration"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}Simply@{ub} send Aust$55 to:
	 	Ben Martin
		Po box 2131
		Southport Queensland
		Australia 4215

	When your registration is received, you will be sent a disk with the latest DzDir 
full version on it. There may also be included versions (possibly beta) of some other 
things that Digital Zenith is working on, these may be for example; a Pim (Personal 
Information Manager, like a FiloFax), a isometric game, or a screenblanker. The 
blanker works fine, but it needs a rather rare and expensive dongle to run (The 
Retina 24 Bit board).


Please include the following;

name/address
your machine type
the version of DzDir that you are using. (Very important)
occupation (if you wish)
your interests (if you wish. This is mainly to see what type of people use Amigas 
these days)

and any @{b}criticism/praise or new ideas@{ub} you have, perhaps the most impor-
tant part.

@EndNode

@Node "Future" "DzDir.guide/Future"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
	The unsure future of DzDir lays...In your hands. The author can't devote all his 
time to its generation anymore. And we at Digital Zenith are quite happy with it, so 
we shan't be adding much to it. We do have a few ideas but were almost out of 'em, 
for DzDir atleast. This might well be the last release if no support is given to DzDir.

Current Ideas;

More detailed arexx interface.
Better Drag And Drop for button configuratiion.
@{b}I-Net support@{ub}
Perhaps a picture viewer, but to compete with the ample Pd (public domain) software 
would be hard and fruitless. However we have just written a viewer that uses 
MUI 2.1's Bitmap class. If you complain enough (we don't think you will) then 
we'll add it. We also have a version for the retina, but it is very much the same 
as "RetinaDisplay" in terms of speed.

	If you have any ideas that you think a "Directory" utility should have then 
please tell us. And most importantly, @{b}@{"REGISTER!" Link "Registration"} 
;-)@{ub}
@EndNode
@Node "Internal" "DzDir.guide/Internal"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
@{b}·Active>->Other@{ub}
	Copy the active filelist's directory to the other filelist.

@{b}·Active<->Other@{ub}
	Exchange the directories of the filelists.

@{b}·Add Icon@{ub}
	Add the icon that is setup for the object that a left click points at to the se-
lected files. Also works for files in a Lha.

@{b}·Configure DataTypes@{ub}
	Bring up the datatypes configuration window.

@{b}·Copy@{ub}
	If a file exists with the same name then you may rename it on the fly, this 
follows the rename function's parameters. You can also replace all.

@{b}·CopyAs@{ub}
	Copy, but ask for a new name for each object.

@{b}·Delete@{ub}
	Can convert protected files to non-protected ones on the fly, and convert all. 
Skip all files that cause errors. Delete all directorys selected.

@{b}·Directories first@{ub}
	Sort he filelists with directories first.

@{b}·Directories last@{ub}
	Sort he filelists with directories last.

@{b}·Directories mixed@{ub}
	Sort he filelists with directories placed to comply with your "sort by" field.

@{b}·Edit Icon@{ub}
	Change the tooltypes, view the icon image, etc. The same as the Workbench 
"Icon/Information..." command.

@{b}·File size@{ub}
	Calculate the size of the selected files/directories.

@{b}·File information@{ub}
	This is a internal which accepts flags. if you don't tell it to Ignore arguments 
then for each argument the filetype is shown. Also the src/dst directory selected 
file/dir info sizes of selected and free disk, together with the % Fit. The filewindows 
must be open for this command to work.

@{b}·@{"Grep" Link "grep"}

@{b}·Left Action@{ub}
	The same as double clicking on a file.

@{b}·Makedir@{ub}
	Just asks for the new directory's name and makes it.

@{b}·Make softlink@{ub}
	Make a softlink from the selected file(s), DzDir will ask for the link's name.

@{b}·Make filetype@{ub}
	Make a new filetype from the selected file(s), DzDir will ask for the types 
	name, and display correlation.
	@{"see: Instant Filetype Creation   " Link "IFC"}

@{b}·Move@{ub}
	If a file exists with the same name then you may rename it on the fly, this 
follows the rename function's parameters. You may also replace/skip all files that al-
ready exist.

@{b}·MoveAs@{ub}
	Move, but ask for a new name for each object.

@{b}·New Shell@{ub}
	Open a shell in the directory of the source directory window. You will need a 
	file in S: called DzShell-Startup.

@{b}·Open file windows@{ub}
 	Open the directory windows.

@{b}·Parent@{ub}
	Display the parent directory to that which is in the current directory window.

@{b}·Parse Files@{ub}
	Ask for a command and execute it on all selected files.

@{b}·Pattern files@{ub}
	Filter the filelists according to set parameters. See @{"filtering" Link 
"Filtration"} for more about the filter class.

@{b}·Quit@{ub}
	Exit the program. 

@{b}·Rename@{ub}
	Will check if a file exists with the given name, if so it will reprompt you for a 
	new name. DzDir will do this until a filename is reached or you choose to 
	replace the file with that name.

@{b}·ReRead Directory@{ub}
	Update the active filelist.

@{b}·Reselect files@{ub}
	Reselects the files you had selected. eg. You have 100 files highlighted and 
are about to shift select another but, you slip on the shift key, and now have 
only one or two file(s) selected! So now you can "Reselect" what you had se-
lected before the tragedy. If you reselect again you undo the previous rese-
lect, working like a toggle.

@{b}·Right Action@{ub}
	The same as double clicking the right mouse button on clicking a file.

@{b}·Root@{ub}
	Display the root directory to that which is in the current directory window.

@{b}·Search@{ub}
	Search the selected directories for certain files. Based on a filter class you tell 
DzDir what your looking for. See @{"filtering" Link "Filtration"} for more about the fil-
ter class.

@{b}·Select@{ub}
	Based on a filter class you can select/deselect/toggle files that match the 
specifitions you set. See @{"filtering" Link "Filtration"} for more about the filter class.

@{b}·Select all@{ub}
	Highlight all of the files in the active directory window.

@{b}·Select none@{ub}
	Highlight none of the files in the active directory window.

@{b}·Select toggle@{ub}
	Highlight all unhighlighted files in the active directory window and unhighlight 
the ones that are currently highlighted.

@{b}·Touch Icon@{ub}
	If you extract a Lha, then the new icons will not have appeared in a Work-
bench window for that directory, if you touch them then they will appear in the work-
bench window in (near) real time.

@{b}·View Text@{ub}
	View a selected file with the output capturing method of DzDir. If you make 
this viewer 'hot' then any files you request to load after now with a matching path will 
be loaded into this window, otherwise a new window is made.

@EndNode
@Node "grep" "DzDir.guide/Grep"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

	You can grep files and directories for strings or regular expressions and DzDir 
will show a list of all the files matching the discription. 
	You can save and load the output of a grep action via buttons on the panel.
	You can also select between fast and slow grep, the differance being that fast 
grep uses no pattern matching. If you hit return after entering a string the default is a 
fast grep, but if the string you entered has a '#?' in it the greping will switch to slow 
grep. You can also select which type you want from the GUI.

	 The slow grep regular expressions work like file pattern matching. For exam-
ple e#? would find lines sarting witth "e" or "E", and #?e would find lines ending in 
"e" or "E" 

	The patterns are fairly extensive, and approximate some of the ability
	of Unix/grep "regular expression" patterns.  Here are the available
	tokens:

	?	Matches a single character.
	#	Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
	(ab|cd)	Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
	~	Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
		that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
		strings that are not exactly "foo").
	[abc]	Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
	[~bc]	Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
		class.
	a-z	Character range (only within character classes). 
	%	Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
	*	Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
		as an option that can be turned on.

	"Expression" in the above table means either a single character
	(ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
	class (ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").


@EndNode

@Node "History" "DzDir.guide/History"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
	DzDir was born in the december of 1993. At the time the two directory utilities 
that I concidered the major players were Dw 1.62 and V4 of Dopus (I think it was V4) 
and these were (and are still) great directory management solutions. That said they 
were at either ends of a spectrum, Dopus being large and powerful, and Dw being 
very fast and small. But nothing was both powerful and resourse friendly. This is 
when I decided to write a program that used MUI and could supply very fast small 
code, but also be very powerful and graphicly pritty. 
	So now in '97 I have this Object oriented program that although its large still 
runs fast and has very many tricks (eg. make a button a path list) because of its de-
sign. It also has a relational database inbuilt to make change to its configuration very 
easy and avoid the problems associated with a first normal format database.


	Revision history was not kept over DzDir's youth, consequently it begins at 
version 9.10.

@{b}New in version 9.20@{ub}; 2 Major bug(s) fixed.
·	Fixed a buf in the Unique key generator of the object database

·	If you try to open a dock that is to large for your screen then it becomes a vir-
tual group in that dock so the window will open. This is very inefficient and you 
are better to then edit that dock and make it either smaller or virtual on a per-
minant basis. 

·	Qualified file showing is now ok. You can configure a qualifier (in menu select 
Edit/Main), then when you have a filelist active (and its window) if you hold 
that qualifier down and type an "S" (no quotes) then the first file begining with 
and "S" will be shown in the filelist. If you keep the qualifier down and type a 
"Z" then the first file begining with "SZ" is shown. You can keep concatinating 
letters for a more defined selection until you deselect the qualifier, then the 
process is repeated.

·	Began to update the structure and contents of the documentation to be more 
reader friendly and imformative.
@EndNode
@Node "Concept" "DzDir.guide/Concept"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
	Because we spend so many hours getting data where we want it on disk and 
retreaving it form this known structure; doing this in a fast, elegant, powerful and 
graphicaly agreeable manner is what DzDir is made of.
	The simple challange DzDir tries to achive is giving the power of unix type 
systems to those who don't want to use a shell. 
@EndNode
@Node "Installation" "DzDir.guide/Installation"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

	DzDir requires the Installer program from Commodore for its installation. 
Therefore installing DzDir is basic, just open the install script and away you go.

@EndNode
